  pm-nilh,related,"2026-07-06T23:36:18.776Z",null,null
body: "The scale spectrum is anchored only at the top: pm-g2zz promises a correct bounded working set at a million items, and pm-4k6b's acceptance already demands small-workspace neutrality of the relevance engine. Nothing anchors the opposite end of the product promise — a project of a few items spanning minutes, where pm is an agent's throwaway working memory for a single session.\n\nAt that scale the costs that matter are ceremony and fixed overhead, not throughput:\n- Quick capture: create with just a type and title must be a complete, valid item under a scratch/minimal metadata profile (the core profile's required author/acceptance-criteria/estimate is the right default for durable repos, but is pure friction for a 5-item scratch pad); the profile family already exists — this story makes the scratch tier a first-class, documented default option on init.\n- Fixed token envelopes: context/next/list output on a 3-item workspace should cost tokens proportional to those 3 items; any constant boilerplate (headers, hints, empty facets) dominates at this scale and is exactly what the lean-output family (pm-nilh, pm-cfed, pm-g9xk) trims — this story adds the small-end assertion to the pm-cu1i budget corpus so it cannot regress.\n- Startup cost is already solved (ADR pm-irp1, esbuild bundle pm-gt82) and stays covered by its shipped budget.\n\nTogether with pm-g2zz this completes the pair of spectrum-ends stories the roadmap optimizes between: same commands, same philosophy, from a seconds-old scratch pad to a decades-old million-item workspace."
